defaultQ4 defaultHowdefault have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?default&#xa0;default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is of concern that the BBC’s reigning in of Lonely Planet and also BBC Jam came relatively late, after widespread concerns were raised, including by this Committee, and, as a result, at considerable additional cost to the licence fee payer, as well as after unnecessary uncertainty in the wider market.
default 
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultQ5 defaultWhatdefault role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?default&#xa0;
default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOur concern here is that the BBC should not have an undue impact on the market. We are not convinced that the BBC governance system is robust enough, as we outline in response to Question 7.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ6 defaultHowdefault should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?default&#xa0;defaultIs there a case for distributing funding for public service content more widely beyond the BBC? What comparisons can be made with the provision of public servdefaultice content in other countries?default&#xa0;
default6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFunding is already being distributed beyond the BBC, 
defaultfor example to support S4C
default. 
defaultWhether licence fee funding should be distributed to other parties is a major debate that may warrant discussion during the Charter renewal process.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ7 defaultHowdefault should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016? In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?default&#xa0;
default7.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Charter clearly requires separation between
default Management and the BBC Trust, 
defaultstating
default that: 
default“The members of the Trust and the members of the Board shall never act together as a single corporate body.”
default 
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Charter goes on to say that: “The Trust must maintain its independence of the Executive Board.”
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultYet Management and Trust have acted together on issues of the highest importance. Most recently, in the wake of the critical NAO report and PAC hearing, the Director General and the Chairman of the Trust wrote jointly to the Secretary of State for Culture, Media &amp; Sport to promise a review of the BBC’s governance.
default This letter promised that the Director General and the Chairman “will together lead this piece of work, drawing on internal resourc
defaultes from both parts of the BBC.”
default&#xa0;
default7.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe view this joint approach as raising serious questions over the effectiveness of the Charter’s requirement for separation, and as particularly ill-
defaultadvised as it is a review of 
defaultthe BBC’s governance systems. Put simply, the body being governed is jointly leading the review into how it is governed. This is a scenario 
defaultwe cannot 
defaultenvisage 
defaulthappening 
defaultfor any other UK broadcaster, yet the BBC, with its privilege of public funding, should be held to the highest standards. 
default&#xa0;
default7.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe also note that this form of joint response
default has occurred before, when Management and the BBC Trust issued a joint response to 
defaultOfcom’s
default second review of Public Service Broadcasting (which was looking at granting some of the licence fee to other services).
default&#xa0;
default7.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn addition, as we have noted previously, the way BBC Management announced changes to the 
defaultiPlayer
default recently raises questions as to the level of oversight that the Trust has. The changes to the 
defaultiPlayer
default could have negative consequences on the rest of the market. Yet Management made 
defaultpublic announcements regarding the new 
defaultiPlayer
default features as if they were a near certainty,
default despite the fact that they had not received Trust approval. In a highly competitive commercial online marketplace, where UK media companies are striving to gain even a minimal foothold, this creates unnecessary uncertainty, and calls into question how the BBC is governed.
default&#xa0;default7.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTo restore the confidence of industry, not to mention the public, BBC governance will require a far greater level of transparency
default, robustness and clarity – and crucially there must be a clear and guaranteed separation between Management and whichever body oversees it.
default It may also require greater resources
default being allocated to the oversight body
default, in order to ensure it
default is able to perform this function properly
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultConstitutional framework
default&#xa0;
default7.8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Charter and Agreement are sufficiently high level for the BBC to have an appropriate level of flexibility in most areas. 
